I"<p>Welcome! I am Baihao Zhang (张柏豪), a PhD candidate in Modern History and German Studies at Sorbonne Nouvelle in Paris. <label for="profile" class="margin-toggle">⊕</label><input type="checkbox" id="profile" class="margin-toggle" /><span class="marginnote"><img class="fullwidth" src="/assets/img/profile.jpg" /><br />👤 Baihao Zhang, 张柏豪<br />✉️ baihao.zhang@sorbonne-nouvelle.fr</span> My doctoral research, supported by a scholarship from the China Scholarship Council (CSC), is now conducted under the joint supervision of <a href="https://www.sorbonne-nouvelle.fr/m-owzar-armin-231917.kjsp">Prof. Armin Owzar</a> (Sorbonne Nouvelle) and <a href="https://www.uni-potsdam.de/de/kulturen-der-aufklaerung/personal/prof-dr-iwan-michelangelo-daprile">Prof. Iwan-Michelangelo D’Aprile</a> (University of Potsdam).</p>

<p>My primary research interest is modern European intellectual history, with a focus on French and German thought during the “long nineteenth century”. I have published several articles in journals and conference proceedings on topics including Rousseau, Wilhelm von Humboldt, and the methodology of intellectual history. Currently, I am preparing my <a href="https://theses.fr/s385749">doctoral dissertation</a> on the fates and ideas of German “Bonapartists” during the Napoleonic era.</p>

<p>On this website, you can also find my Chinese translation of Thomas Nipperdey’s <em>Deutsche Geschichte</em>. A foundational text in modern German history, its importance is matched only by Hans-Ulrich Wehler’s <em>Deutsche Gesellschaftsgeschichte</em>. I began this personal project a year ago and continue to update it periodically. It is shared <a href="/nipperdey/">here</a> for the benefit of interested readers and researchers.</p>

